am, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Brus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Polish, Slovenian, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Slavic <i>brus</i> ‘whetstone’, presumably a metonymic occupational name for someone who honed or sharpened blades; possibly also a nickname for a clumsy or coarse fellow. Compare   Bruss  .","Slovenian: from an old dialect short form of the personal name <i>Ambrož</i> (see   Ambrose  ). Compare   Bruss  .","French: topographic name for someone living on a heath, from Occitan <i>brusc</i> ‘heather’, or a habitational name from (Le/Les) Brus, the name of several places in southern France."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Eldor, Reinhard, Rudie, Wilhelm.","German (also <b>Brüss</b>): from a short form of the medieval personal name <i>Ambrosius</i> (see   Ambrose  ).","Americanized or Germanized form of Polish, Slovenian, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic)   Brus  , meaning ‘whetstone’ and, as a Slovenian name, also ‘Ambrose’."]}]},{"name":"Constance","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Late Latin name <i>Constantia</i>, which is either a feminine derivative of <i>Constans</i> (  see  Constant  ) or an abstract noun meaning ‘constancy’. This was a popular name among the Normans, and was borne by, amongst others, the formidable Constance of Sicily (  1158